## .NET 8 Migration: `TimedExecutor`

### Key Breaking Changes

1. **`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** in .NET Core+. It was removed because it could corrupt process state by unwinding at arbitrary points.
2. **`Thread.ResetAbort()` also removed** — no longer needed.
3. The idiomatic replacement is **`CancellationToken` + `Task.Run`**.

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
        var task = Task.Run(work, cts.Token);

        try
        {
            // Block until completion or timeout
            if (task.Wait(timeout))
                return task.Result;

            // Signal cancellation (cooperative — won't force-kill)
            cts.Cancel();
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        catch (AggregateException ex) when (ex.InnerExceptions.Count == 1)
        {
            // Unwrap single exceptions to match original behavior
            throw ex.InnerExceptions[0];
        }
    }

    // Prefer this async overload in new code
    public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(
        Func<CancellationToken, Task<T>> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            return await work(cts.Token);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

### Critical Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---|---|
| **Cancellation is cooperative** | Unlike `Thread.Abort()`, cancellation only works if `work` checks `CancellationToken`. CPU-bound loops that ignore the token **will not stop**. |
| **`task.Result` vs `await`** | `.Result` wraps exceptions in `AggregateException`; `await` unwraps automatically. The sync overload above handles this. |
| **Fire-and-forget leak** | After timeout, the abandoned `Task.Run` keeps running. If the work holds resources (DB connections, file handles), they won't be released until it finishes naturally. |
| **Thread pool starvation** | `Task.Run` uses the ThreadPool, not a dedicated thread. Long-blocking work can starve other tasks. Use `Task.Factory.StartNew(..., TaskCreationOptions.LongRunning)` if needed. |

### Usage

```csharp
var executor = new TimedExecutor();

// Sync (backward-compatible call sites)
var value = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(() => SlowComputation(), TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));

// Async (preferred in new code — work can observe cancellation)
var result = await executor.ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync(async ct =>
{
    return await httpClient.GetStringAsync(url, ct);
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));
```

**Bottom line:** There is no safe equivalent to `Thread.Abort()`. Redesign long-running work to accept and poll a `CancellationToken` — that's the only reliable way to enforce timeouts in .NET 8.
